# README and Documentation Guidelines

When working with README.md and other documentation files:

## README Structure

- Start with a clear project title and description
- Include a comprehensive table of contents for longer documents
- Provide installation and setup instructions
- Document usage examples with code snippets
- Include a project structure overview
- Add contribution guidelines if applicable
- Reference related documentation and external resources

## Documentation Best Practices

- Use clear, concise language appropriate for the target audience
- Include code examples that actually work
- Keep information up to date with project changes
- Use consistent formatting and styling
- Add links to relevant external documentation
- Include troubleshooting sections for common issues

## Markdown Formatting

- Use proper heading hierarchy (# ## ### ####)
- Format code blocks with appropriate language tags
- Use backticks for inline code and file names
- Create clear lists with consistent bullet points
- Add horizontal rules to separate major sections
- Include links using descriptive text rather than raw URLs

## Content Guidelines

- Explain not just what but why
- Provide context for configuration options
- Include expected outcomes and examples
- Document any prerequisites or dependencies
- Add version information where relevant
- Keep language professional but approachable

## Maintenance

- Review and update regularly
- Test all code examples and links
- Keep screenshots and diagrams current
- Ensure consistency with actual project state
- Update based on user feedback and questions

